
*******************************************************************************

 Your new CloudKit app has been generated.
 
*******************************************************************************

 CloudKit is a toolkit for building Open Web applications.
 
 To quote the GitHub landing page, CloudKit is a
   
   "RESTful, cross-platform, cross-browser, online/offline, hybrid web/desktop,
    multi-client data synchronization platform"
 
 Here's your checklist to get things started:
 
 1) Create your database, migrate the schema and start the app:
 
    > mysqladmin -uroot create <your_app_name>_development
    > cd <your_app_name>
    > rake db:migrate
    > rake start
    ... visit http://localhost:3000 to see the scaffolding.
    
    At this point, you have a working app that supports OpenID sign ups and
    logins, OAuth API authorization, and code generators for rapid development.
    
    To test OAuth access, follow the link after logging in to create an
    authorized client app. Then use something like Endpointr:
    
    http://github.com/jcrosby/endpointr/tree/master
    
    to hit the standard OAuth API access points:
    
    http://localhost:3000/oauth/request_token (Request Token)
    http://localhost:3000/oauth/authorize (Authorization URL)
    http://localhost:3000/oauth/access_token (Access Token)
    http://localhost:3000/oauth/echo?word=hello (Protected Resource Example)
 
 2) To generate a contextually aware UI for your app, make sure you have
    GWT installed, then:
 
    > script/generate gwt_client --gwt-home=/usr/local/lib/gwt
    
    Follow the directions after generating your GWT app to generate a
    desktop version that uses CloudKit's contextual awareness to change
    behavior based on web service availability (online/offline), desktop
    version updates, schema migrations, etc.
 
*******************************************************************************

